std::thread::spawn creates an OS thread. Each thread has its own stack (typically 2-8 MB), and the OS schedules them. Good for CPU-bound work. Creating thousands of threads is expensive.

std::thread::spawn(|| {
    // Runs on a separate OS thread
    heavy_computation();
});

tokio::spawn creates an async task. Tasks are lightweight (a few hundred bytes of state) and are multiplexed onto a thread pool by the tokio runtime. Good for I/O-bound work. You can spawn millions of tasks.

tokio::spawn(async {
    // Runs on tokio's thread pool
    network_request().await;
});

Key differences:
- Threads: preemptive scheduling by OS, expensive, good for CPU work
- Tasks: cooperative scheduling by runtime, cheap, good for I/O work
- Threads can block freely; tasks must not block (use spawn_blocking)

The standard pattern is Arc<Mutex<T>> or Arc<RwLock<T>>:

use std::sync::Arc;
use tokio::sync::Mutex;

let state = Arc::new(Mutex::new(HashMap::new()));

for i in 0..10 {
    let state = Arc::clone(&state);
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        let mut guard = state.lock().await;
        guard.insert(i, i * 10);
    });
}

Alternatives depending on the use case:
- tokio::sync::Mutex: async-aware, can hold lock across .await points
- std::sync::Mutex: lighter, but holding across .await can block runtime threads
- DashMap: concurrent HashMap without explicit locking
- Channels (mpsc): message-passing instead of shared state
- watch channel: for a single value that changes over time

Best practice: prefer channels (message passing) over shared mutable state when possible. It is easier to reason about and less prone to deadlocks.
